1 3 3-2 58. Aeneas, having spoken, was first to call upon the Gods, and Jupiter showed approval by thrice thundering in a cloudless sky, so that all the T rojans knew their wanderings were ended. Next day, while some explored the land, an embassage was sent to Latinus, asking his consent to the incursion. While Aeneas drew out the plan of the city to be built, the Latins, occupied in military exercises without the town, perceived the envoys approaching. They were ushered to the presence of Latinus in the Court of a hundred pillars, the meeting-place of his C ouncil‚ adorned with statues of the great ones of old.
